Q1
conficence interval (CI): a good interval to estimate the mean of a target variable without knowing true population parameter. For instance, the 95% of CI of new born weight is 6lb to 9lb meaning we are 95% confident to conclude that mean weight of new born population will fall within this range. PI: a good interval to estimate the a future target variable wll fall, given a sets of current observations/statistical parameters. For example, given multiple pedictors for a linear regression model, we train the model with values of predictors and predict a prediction interval of 6lb to 8.5lb. We can say that 95% confidence that birth weight of next baby provided with same model will lie in this range. Generally, PI is much wider than CI since it is more challenging to estimate an individual value instead of mean of population. When we want to know specific predicted value we need to calculate PI.

# impute NA
## impute numerical var with median
ncbirths <- ncbirths %>% 
  mutate_if(is.numeric, function(x) ifelse(is.na(x), median(x, na.rm = T), x))

## impute categorical var with mode
get_mode <- function(x){
  uniq_val <- unique(x)
  count_unique <- tabulate(match(x, uniq_val))
  uniq_val[which.max(count_unique)]
}

###premie
ncbirths$premie[is.na(ncbirths$premie)] <- get_mode(ncbirths$premie)


### marital
ncbirths$marital[is.na(ncbirths$marital)] <- get_mode(ncbirths$marital)

### habit
ncbirths$habit[is.na(ncbirths$habit)] <- get_mode(ncbirths$habit)

### whitemom
ncbirths$whitemom[is.na(ncbirths$whitemom)] <- get_mode(ncbirths$whitemom)

Inspection of correlation matrix reveals that there are several predictors may exist multicollinearity in the model. Could take a look at each class distribution of binary variables, which could raise imblanced classification (not consider here). - First of all, looking at distribution of each variables: + Normal distribution: father age, visits, gained, weight + Uniform distribution: mother age, gender + Skewed distribution: weeks (most are between 37 and 40), mature (mostly younger mom), premie (mostly full-term), lowbirthweight (mostly not low), habit(mostly non-smoker), whitemom (mostly whitemom) - multicollinearity: + 0.71 for fage and mage + 0.64 for mage and mature + 0.74 for weeks and premie + 0.55 for premie and weight + 0.67 for weeks and weight In general, high multicollinearity could affect p-value and coefficients when being used in the model. However, it wont affect predictions or goodness of fit. Some variables such as mature since its correlation with weight is only 0.01.

The Multiple R-squared is 0.6406 and Adjusted R-squared 0.6363 meaning most variables are explained by the model as they dont differ much. The residual standard error (RSE) is 0.91 and I calculate the error rate, which is 13%. Not bad The F-statistic is 146.6 , p-value is < 2.2e-16 indicating statistically signifcant. For individual p-values of coefficients, there are few values greater than 0.05 and they are not statistically significant in the model. They are fage, mage, mature, premie, visits and marital. The other variables such as weeks, gained, lowbirthweight, gender, habit, and whitemom are statistically significant.

The predicted weight is 8.06648. The 95% confidence interval is 7.915943 to 8.217017. The 95% prediction interval is 6.276752 to 9.856207. The prediction interval is wider than confident interval since more uncertainty will be added to predict a single value than a mean weight.
